1
00:00:00,875 --> 00:00:05,291
We left this room and went into one of the investigation rooms

2
00:00:06,250 --> 00:00:12,291
One of them grabbed my hand and
cuffed me, while the other walked behind me

3
00:00:13,250 --> 00:00:18,166
They took me from here, there were rooms here of course

4
00:00:21,666 --> 00:00:26,500
There were solitary cells, and here
I don’t remember what was there

5
00:00:26,791 --> 00:00:33,458
Here there was a man suspended by his limbs, shackled
like this in this area, he was the one groaning and crying

6
00:00:34,666 --> 00:00:41,625
They brought me in from here. This was the
solitary cell I was in. I stayed in this spot

7
00:00:41,625 --> 00:00:43,291
Interviewer: What did the solitary cell contain?

8
00:00:43,333 --> 00:00:49,583
The solitary cell was large and had a toilet and a sink

9
00:00:51,166 --> 00:00:58,333
This wall ended here. It was clear there was
a wall, and there was a toilet in the corner

10
00:00:59,458 --> 00:01:06,958
And there was a water tap in the solitary cells, that’s it

11
00:01:09,791 --> 00:01:11,875
Interviewer: How long did you stay in this solitary cell?

12
00:01:11,875 --> 00:01:19,416
I stayed in this solitary cell for about a week or more than a week

13
00:01:19,708 --> 00:01:22,000
I don’t remember exactly how many days, I didn’t count

14
00:01:22,083 --> 00:01:25,166
Interviewer: How did you spend your day in the solitary cell?

15
00:01:25,166 --> 00:01:33,083
There were books in this area, like a small
library above, and we would read the books

16
00:01:33,916 --> 00:01:36,041
Interviewer: What kind of books were there?

17
00:01:36,666 --> 00:01:45,333
Books like Sahih al-Bukhari, the Prophet’s
hadiths, the Quran, and other religious books

18
00:01:47,041 --> 00:01:55,041
Interviewer: Did diseases spread in the prison
like lice and scabies, or was there attention to hygiene?

19
00:01:56,250 --> 00:02:04,166
In the solitary cell, there were absolutely
no diseases because I was alone in the cell

20
00:02:04,208 --> 00:02:12,000
And I cleaned it, but in the group cells I don’t know if there
were, though I don’t think so because no one ever mentioned diseases

21
00:02:13,625 --> 00:02:21,625
Interviewer: Did you ever get sick and receive medicine
or see a doctor? Was there any medical care for prisoners?

22
00:02:23,208 --> 00:02:30,916
For me, when I had a headache,
they would give me a painkiller, that’s all

23
00:02:32,041 --> 00:02:39,541
Other than that, I don’t know, but I think if someone got sick, they
would bring him a doctor or give him medicine if it was a mild illness

24
00:02:40,125 --> 00:02:48,125
Interviewer: Were the meals provided regularly—breakfast,
lunch, and dinner—or were they limited?

25
00:02:48,458 --> 00:02:56,416
They served multiple meals regularly

26
00:02:56,583 --> 00:03:00,791
Breakfast, lunch, and dinner, and every day something different

27
00:03:07,083 --> 00:03:13,125
Breakfast was simple, like jam, labneh, and cheese

28
00:03:13,208 --> 00:03:20,291
Lunch was sometimes cooked food, sometimes ready food,
and sometimes sandwiches, and dinner was the same

29
00:03:21,333 --> 00:03:28,625
Interviewer: Did you communicate with other prisoners
in solitary cells since you were alone in your room?

30
00:03:28,666 --> 00:03:35,625
Did you try to talk to anyone or hear someone you knew?

31
00:03:36,041 --> 00:03:43,125
Of course, I was in the solitary cell, and I would
get bored. When they brought people into the next cell

32
00:03:43,958 --> 00:03:49,083
Sometimes I tried to talk to them, but no one
replied, no one could reply, they were afraid

33
00:03:49,125 --> 00:03:53,625
In the end, I stopped trying to talk
for fear someone outside might hear

34
00:03:55,000 --> 00:03:59,541
They didn’t beat me except the first time I was
brought here, when one of them hit my shoulder

35
00:04:01,250 --> 00:04:08,750
Interviewer: We know most prisoners write their names
or memories on the wall, did you write your name?

36
00:04:08,791 --> 00:04:12,083
No, I didn’t write my name, a memory, or anything at all

37
00:04:14,083 --> 00:04:21,791
Interviewer: Who were the jailers that came into your solitary cell?
Who were they, what was their accent, and how did they treat you?

38
00:04:22,125 --> 00:04:27,916
Their treatment of me was normal, not harsh

39
00:04:31,916 --> 00:04:37,000
The jailers who came to me treated me normally

40
00:04:38,291 --> 00:04:43,666
With respect, they didn’t like dealing
with prisoners unless necessary

41
00:04:46,583 --> 00:04:54,583
Interviewer: Did you or any of the prisoners here try
to escape from prison? Was there an escape attempt?

42
00:04:55,625 --> 00:05:04,291
In prison, I heard about an escape attempt, but I
never thought about escaping, not even privately

43
00:05:05,458 --> 00:05:10,416
Interviewer: Did you know the people who
tried to escape or the details of the plan?

44
00:05:11,041 --> 00:05:19,041
I don’t know the escape details, but I know
some people tried to escape from Burj Prison

45
00:05:19,833 --> 00:05:26,291
But they couldn’t, they were caught, and I, in
the solitary cell, never thought about escaping

46
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:30,000
Interviewer: Was the prison ever bombed while you were there?

47
00:05:30,791 --> 00:05:35,416
No, the prison was never bombed
while I was there, the bombing was outside

48
00:05:35,916 --> 00:05:40,708
In the nearby area, but Burj Prison itself wasn’t bombed

49
00:05:42,875 --> 00:05:49,416
Interviewer: Do you have a story or
memory from your time alone in this room?

50
00:05:49,916 --> 00:05:55,541
Do you have a story or incident that happened to you?

51
00:05:56,166 --> 00:06:03,083
One story that happened to me here was when I was in this solitary
cell and there was a <i>balingo</i> [suspension hoist] outside

52
00:06:03,250 --> 00:06:10,500
They brought people there, and I could hear their voices,
their torture, and their beating, I couldn’t imagine it

53
00:06:10,583 --> 00:06:14,958
They took me for interrogation and brought me
back. I still didn’t know what my charge was

54
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:22,500
Finally, two days before I was released, they told
me my charge was belonging to the Free Syrian Army

55
00:06:23,583 --> 00:06:31,000
And possessing a weapon, that’s what happened with me

56
00:06:33,416 --> 00:06:38,083
In the solitary cell, the light was on day and night

57
00:06:41,541 --> 00:06:44,458
Because during the day we couldn’t see, there was no light

58
00:06:46,333 --> 00:06:53,708
Interviewer: How did you feel being here in
solitary? What thoughts occupied your mind?

59
00:06:53,750 --> 00:06:57,625
What were you thinking about while in this place?

60
00:06:57,833 --> 00:07:04,333
When I was here in solitary, I thought
every day, what will they do to me?

61
00:07:04,375 --> 00:07:08,125
Will they execute me or release
me? Because they killed many people

62
00:07:09,708 --> 00:07:13,041
I didn’t know what my fate would be, that’s what frightened me

63
00:07:13,208 --> 00:07:20,708
In the solitary cell, I had a toilet, a sink, and cleaning tools

64
00:07:21,750 --> 00:07:27,333
And here I had a sponge, a pillow, and a blanket

65
00:07:28,166 --> 00:07:31,875
And here there were shelves for books. That’s what was there

66
00:07:32,375 --> 00:07:38,291
And here there was a chair, and I
used to entertain myself by reading books

67
00:07:38,708 --> 00:07:42,625
Interviewer: How did they bring
you food? How did they give it to you?

68
00:07:42,791 --> 00:07:45,791
They opened the door normally and gave me the food

69
00:07:48,750 --> 00:07:56,750
They didn’t treat me like the other prisoners. They
used to beat them and shout at them and so on

70
00:07:56,791 --> 00:08:04,791
I heard them shouting at others, but for me, they
brought food regularly with politeness and respect

71
00:08:08,208 --> 00:08:13,708
Interviewer: Do you know the nicknames or
names of the jailers who brought you food?

72
00:08:14,250 --> 00:08:19,416
Those who came to my solitary cell brought
me food or medicine or anything I asked for

73
00:08:20,083 --> 00:08:26,333
One was named Abu Abdullah. He was the one who
came to me. And another whose name I didn’t know

74
00:08:26,916 --> 00:08:32,166
Another one was named Shaqran, but mostly it was
Abu Abdullah and that one whose name I didn’t know

75
00:08:32,416 --> 00:08:34,291
Interviewer: Do you remember their features?

76
00:08:34,333 --> 00:08:40,291
Their features, Abu Abdullah was a bit heavyset

77
00:08:41,458 --> 00:08:48,541
He was full-bodied and taller than me,
and the other one had a Syrian accent

78
00:08:49,416 --> 00:08:57,166
Eastern, his body was similar to mine
in height and build, not thin and not fat

79
00:08:58,708 --> 00:09:02,041
Shaqran was thin, thinner
than me, and a bit taller

80
00:09:02,958 --> 00:09:08,416
Interviewer: Did the prisoners and jailers have a uniform or not?

81
00:09:09,208 --> 00:09:16,458
No, they wore black, the jailers wore black

82
00:09:17,208 --> 00:09:23,958
And they were masked or wore <i>shishaniyat</i> [a knee-length garment], and military clothing

83
00:09:25,291 --> 00:09:32,875
Interviewer: Were there visits? Were your
family allowed to visit you or bring you things?

84
00:09:33,500 --> 00:09:37,041
Of course, here in Burj Prison there were absolutely no visits

85
00:09:38,208 --> 00:09:42,625
My family didn’t visit me, no one did,
my family didn’t even know where I was

86
00:09:45,250 --> 00:09:49,291
Interviewer: In prison, did you stay in your
own clothes or were uniforms distributed?

87
00:09:49,875 --> 00:09:56,791
They distributed uniforms to us, and
in the solitary cell they gave me one

88
00:09:57,750 --> 00:10:03,291
They gave me two uniforms, and they were changed
once a week, and I had my own clothes too

89
00:10:03,625 --> 00:10:07,958
Interviewer: Tell us about the uniform’s
features and color, was there anything on it?

90
00:10:08,666 --> 00:10:16,208
There was nothing on it, the uniform was blue with no writing

91
00:10:16,250 --> 00:10:21,541
No flag, symbol, or anything, it was plain

92
00:10:23,916 --> 00:10:27,541
Interviewer: Were there mediations or connections in the prison?

93
00:10:33,375 --> 00:10:37,833
Were there prisoners who were tortured more than others?

94
00:10:38,875 --> 00:10:42,833
As for mediations in their prison, I don’t think there were any

95
00:10:43,833 --> 00:10:48,583
Whoever was proven guilty was beaten,
tortured, imprisoned, and sentenced

96
00:10:49,208 --> 00:10:53,250
And whoever wasn’t proven guilty wasn’t beaten, that’s how it was

97
00:10:53,833 --> 00:10:58,083
Interviewer: What’s the difference between
the Hisba and the other ISIS branches?

98
00:10:58,291 --> 00:11:04,833
And regarding ISIS security branches,
which one did people fear the most?

99
00:11:05,708 --> 00:11:13,333
During ISIS’s days, what people feared most
were the security officers, especially young men

100
00:11:14,541 --> 00:11:20,791
The young men of our generation were afraid of the security
officers because whoever entered their prisons never came out

101
00:11:21,750 --> 00:11:27,458
This was the norm, but the Hisba (religious
police) also terrorized people in general

102
00:11:27,958 --> 00:11:35,958
Because they forced women to wear the <i>niqab</i> [face veil],
and ordered shops to close during the call to prayer

103
00:11:36,333 --> 00:11:41,333
Everyone had to go to the mosque at prayer time. People feared that,
as well as the rules about the <i>izar</i> [long pants], hair, and beards

104
00:11:41,791 --> 00:11:47,250
Interviewer: Regarding the prison’s cleanliness, you
were in a solitary cell, but what about the group cells?

105
00:11:47,916 --> 00:11:55,916
Were the guards responsible for cleaning, or did the
prisoners share the duties of cooking and cleaning?

106
00:11:57,875 --> 00:12:04,916
As for cleanliness in prison, I can tell you about the
solitary cell. I was the one who cleaned it since I was alone

107
00:12:04,958 --> 00:12:10,166
But regarding the group cells, I’m not sure whether they cleaned
them themselves, brought someone in to clean, or took turns doing it

108
00:12:12,000 --> 00:12:19,416
Interviewer: What did the smell of that place feel like?

109
00:12:19,958 --> 00:12:24,458
The one still linked to your memory until this day

110
00:12:25,791 --> 00:12:33,666
As for that place, there wasn’t any specific smell

111
00:12:33,750 --> 00:12:41,708
But once, I smelled blood. Someone had been beaten severely, and
the smell of blood reached me. I stayed in the room for two days

112
00:12:46,833 --> 00:12:52,000
Interviewer: Were there any new words or expressions used in prison

113
00:12:52,083 --> 00:12:55,500
That you hadn’t heard before in your normal life—new words to you?

114
00:12:57,875 --> 00:13:04,458
The words and expressions there were all familiar

115
00:13:05,500 --> 00:13:09,291
Sometimes they spoke in Standard Arabic. I could hear
them from outside of course—they didn’t come inside

116
00:13:10,541 --> 00:13:13,416
That was all, while the rest I understood normally

117
00:13:15,000 --> 00:13:23,000
Interviewer: Were there any specific words you heard for
the first time inside prison, any particular new ones?

118
00:13:26,208 --> 00:13:34,208
Specific words in prison—I didn’t notice or pay
attention to whether there was a word I didn’t understand

119
00:13:38,291 --> 00:13:44,541
Interviewer: ISIS used certain titles for administrative roles

120
00:13:44,583 --> 00:13:48,750
Like the <i>sharia</i> judge, the
<i>wali</i> [governor], or the <i>emir</i> [commander]

121
00:13:48,750 --> 00:13:53,916
Interviewer: Explain to us what each title means—what was their role?

122
00:13:53,958 --> 00:13:59,041
For example, what was the <i>wali</i>’s job in
Raqqa? And also the <i>emir</i> and the <i>sharia</i> judge

123
00:14:00,500 --> 00:14:07,000
Of course, regarding the <i>sharia</i>
judge, the <i>emir</i>, and the <i>wali</i>

124
00:14:07,833 --> 00:14:13,916
We used to hear about them, and knew there was a <i>wali</i> and
a <i>sharia</i> judge. The <i>sharia</i> judge was the general judge

125
00:14:14,625 --> 00:14:20,208
He was called <i>sharia</i> judge because he ruled
according to God’s law, from the Quran and the Sunnah

126
00:14:20,916 --> 00:14:31,208
As for the <i>wali</i>, I don’t know his exact function, but I think
he was like a district manager or someone in charge of an area

127
00:14:32,750 --> 00:14:38,000
And the <i>emir</i> was the person responsible for a
specific place, like the prison <i>emir</i> or the army <i>emir</i>
